 Description of the commands:
  @{" Login        " Link Login}  Replacement Login command
  @{" Logout       " Link Logout}  Replacement Logout command
  @{" su           " Link su}  Spawn a new shell under another username
  @{" chmod        " Link chmod}  Change permission bits for files and dirs
  @{" chown/chgrp  " Link chown}  Change owner and/or group of files and dirs
@endnode

@node Introduction "What is it ?"

                               Introduction

  This  package contains 6 usefull support commands for MultiUser (8 if you
count  both chown and chown37 and both chgrp and chgrp37). Needless to say:
If  you  haven't  got MultiUser these 6 commands will be of little value to
you (except chmod which is usefull anyway).
  All 6 commands are ofcourse pure and can be made resident.

  I  got  the  idea  for  @{"Login" Link Login}  from  looking  at  the  autodoc  for  the
multiuser.library/muLogin() function, and noticing that the origional Login
command  did  not  support  all  the  tags  available  in that function, in
particular the public screen tag really should be supported. And also I was
annoyed  that Login didn't set the local variable $Home. So I decided to do
something about it.

  As  for  @{"Logout" Link Logout}  it also missed the public screen tag and only set $Home
when  after  a  logout  the  user stack was empty and a login was forced. I
corrected this and also implemented a INTO and for INTO a PASSWD argument.

  The   idea   for   @{"su" Link su}   came   from   Chris   Mc   Carthy's  su  command
(Aminet:util/cli/su.lha)  which I liked, but also felt missed something, so
I had to add what was missing.

  I  have  a  UNIX  account  at  the  university where I'm studying and has
noticed some similarities between UNIX and AmigaDos, but sometimes the UNIX
commands  are  just  so  much  more  powerful  than the equivalent AmigaDos
commands.  This  is  the case for @{"chmod" Link chmod} vs. Protect/MProtect, @{"chown/chgrp" Link chown}
vs. SetOwner[37]. So I decided to make AmigaDos versions of these commands.
Halfway  finished  with  chmod,  however,  I noticed that there was another
chmod  command  on  Aminet,  but luckily that one was crap and did not work
like UNIX chmod, so my work was not in vain.
@endnode

