@node Login "Login - replacement Login command"

                                   Login

  This  command  is  a replacement for Login from the MultiUser package and
works  basically  the  same, so see MultiUser.doc for unexplained arguments
the  improvements  are  that  the  GUI  switch is automatic, so unless your
pr_WindowPtr  is  -1  and you don't specify a public screen with the PUBSCR
argument  you'll  always  get  a requester. Furthermore unlike the original
login  this  one  always  sets  the  local variable $Home correctly after a
succesful  login.  Also this Login command accepts the following additionel
arguments:


PASSWD    For  automatic  login  you  can  suply  your  password  with this
          argument. Warning: WHEN USING THIS ARGUMENT YOUR PASSWORD WILL BE
          VISIBLE.  You  should  generally  not need to suply this. this is
          here mostly for completeness.

PUBSCR    Normally  the  login  requester  appears at the workbench screen.
          With this argument you can specify a public screen for it to open
          on instead.
@endnode

@node Logout "Logout - replacement Logout command"

                                  Logout

  This  command  is a replacement for Logout from the MultiUser package and
works  basically  the  same, so see MultiUser.doc for unexplained arguments
the  improvements  are  that  the  GUI  switch is automatic, so unless your
pr_WindowPtr  is  -1  and you don't specify a public screen with the PUBSCR
argument  you'll  always  get  a requester. Furthermore unlike the original
Logout  this  one  always  sets  the  local  variable $Home correctly after
Logout.   Also   this  Logout  command  accepts  the  following  additionel
arguments:


INTO      This  is  a  userid  for  logout to try to login as after logout.
          Specifying INTO has the same effect as Logout QUIET, Login.
              Logout INTO ostemad
          is equivalent to:
              Logout QUIET
              Login ostemad

PASSWD    For  automatic  login  with INTO you can suply your password with
          this  argument. See the warning under @{"Login" Link Login}.

PUBSCR    See @{"Login" Link Login}
@endnode

@node su "su - spawn a new shell under another username"

                                    su

                 Spawn a new shell under another username

  After installing MultiUser on my system I downloaded Chris Mc Carthy's su
command  (Aminet:util/cli/su.lha), and I liked the idea, but I also thought
that  his  su  what  too large (5 kb, of which 4 kb is the standard startup
code)  for  something  that  does  so  little,  and  I wanted a little more
functionallity  than  his  su  offered  (not  to mention that his su wasn't
pure), so I made my own su command. Although I have to give Chris Mc Carthy
credit for the idea the code used for this su command is entirely my own.

  Given a userid su will spawn a new shell under that user, like @{"Login" Link Login} and
@{"Logout" Link Logout} su will automatically decide wether or not a graphical login should
be  used.  su  will set the local variable $Home correctly for both the new
shell and the current shell. su accepts the following arguments:


USERID    Spawn a new shell under this user.

PASSWD    For automatic Login. See the warning under @{"Login" Link Login}.

PUBSCR    See @{"Login" Link Login}.


		su ostemad
	is equivalent to:
		Login ostemad
		NewShell
		Logout QUIET
@endnode

@node chmod "chmod - change permission for file and dirs"

                                   chmod

  chmod  changes  the permissions/protection of files and dirs according to
the symbolic mode_list or the absolute numeric_mode.
  chmod  doesn't require MultiUser to work, if multiuser.library V39+ can't
be  opened  chmod  will  simply  fall  back  to dos.library/SetProtection()
instead of multiuser.library/muSetProtection().


    Usage:
	chmod [-v] [-R] [ugoa]+-=[rwexdhuspa][,...] file ...
	chmod [-v] [-R] <ugo> file ...

	where <ugo> is an octal number


    Options
	   -v	verbose
		UNIX commands are usually very quiet and only prints out
		text when there's somekind of error. chmod follows this
		style, but for the "Amiga-style" I implemented this option.
		With the verbose option you can force chmod to report it's
		progress.
		To get a more "Amiga-like" command you can define an alias
		(if you're not used to UNIX this might be a good idea):
			alias chmod "chmod -v"

	   -R	Recursive
		Recursively change the permission/protection bits for all
		files and directories encountered.


  chmod understands all the standard AmigaDos wildcards and you can specify
as many files and/or wildcards as your shell allows you.


    numeric_mode

	usage: chmod [-v] [-R] numeric_mode file ...


	Absolute permissions can be set by specifing a numeric_mode, an
	octal number constructed from the logical OR of the following mode
	bits:


	Permission mode bits:

	   +------------------ 400  read by owner
	   | +---------------- 200  write by owner
	   | | +-------------- 100  execute by owner
	   | | | +------------ 040  read by group
	   | | | | +---------- 020  write by group
	   | | | | | +-------- 010  execute by group
	   | | | | | | +------ 004  read by others
	   | | | | | | | +---- 002  write by others
	   | | | | | | | | +-- 001  execute by others
	   | | | | | | | | |
	   r w e r w e r w e


	Note: In numeric mode chmod sets the 'd' bit to the same value
	      as the 'w' bit (for compatibility with UNIX chmod).
	      If you want the 'w' and 'd' bits to have different values
	      you should use the more powerful symbolic mode.

	Note: The numeric mode leaves the AmigaDos bits (uhspa) unchanged,
	      to change the AmigaDos bits use the more powerful symbolic
	      mode.

	Note: If the 'U' bit is set then the 'w' and 'd' bits for group
	      and other are automatically cleared.
	      (If you really want to have 'w' and/or 'd' bits set
	      at the same time as the 'U' bit use MProtect).



    symbolic_mode
	usage chmod [-v] [-R] mode_list file ...

	A symbolic mode_list is a comma-separated list of elements, each of
	the form:

		[who]op[permission][,...]


	who	Any combination of the following:

		u	Modify permissions for user/owner.
		g	Modify permissions for group.
		o	Modify permissions for others.
		a	Modify permissions for all users (a is
			equivalent to ugo).

		if who is not specified user is assumed.


	op	Must be specified and can be one of the following:

		+	Add permission to the existing file mode
			bits.
		-	Delete permission from the existing file
			mode bits.
		=	Set permission to specified value (discard
			existing mode bits).


	permission  any combination of the following letters:

		r	Add or delete read permission for who.
		w	Add or delete write permission for who.
		e	Add or delete execute permission for who.
		d	Add or delete delete permission for who

		x	Same as e (for compatibility with UNIX chmod).


		AmigaDos bits:

		u	Add or delete the set-user-ID bit (see 
			MultiUser.doc)
		h	Add or delete the hide bit.
		s	Add or delete the script bit.
		p	Add or delete the pure bit
		a	Add or delete the archived bit

		Note: The AmigaDos bits belong to the user, so specifying
		      them if who does not include user will generate an
		      error.

		Note: If the 'U' bit is set then the 'w' and 'd' bits for
		      group and other are automatically cleared.
		      (If you really want to have 'w' and/or 'd' bits set
		      at the same time as the 'U' bit use MProtect).


	Several symbolic modes separated by commas can be given on the same
	command line. If there are any conflicts between the symbolic modes
	given the last specified modes overrides the former ones, for
	example in:
		chmod u+r,u-r file
	u-r overrides u+r because it is specified later than u+r.


    Examples of usage (were possible the equivalent commands with
    MProtect and Protect are also given):


	Make file readable to everybody, give user write permissions
	and clear the dosbits:
		chmod u=rwed,go=re file
		MProtect file rwed group re other re

	Remove all permissions from group and other
		chmod go= file
		chmod go-rwed file
		MProtect file group rwed other rwed sub

	Make file executable to everybody:
		chmod a+e file
		chmod a+x file		(the x is threated like an e)
		MProtect file e group e other e add

	Set the pure bit for file:
		chmod +p file
		Protect file +p
		MProtect file p add

	Set the protection bits appropiatly for the commands in this
	distribution:
	  chmod u=prwed,go=re C:Login C:Logout C:su C:chmod C:chown C:chgrp
@endnode

@node chown "chown/chgrp - change owner and/or group of files and dirs"

                               chown / chgrp

  chown  changes  the ownerID of files and dirs to owner and optionally the
groupID  of  files  and  dirs  to  group. If group is not specified owner's
primary group will be taken.
  chgrp changes the groupID of files and dirs to group.


    Usage:
	chown [-v] [-R] owner[:group] file ...
	chgrp [-v] [-R] group file ...


  The  owner  can  be  either  a decimal user ID, a login name found in the
password  file or '*' for the current task owner. The group can be either a
decimal  group  ID,  a group name found in the group file and with chgrp it
can also be '*' for the current task owner's primary group.


    Options
	   -v	verbose
		UNIX commands are usually very quiet and only prints out
		text when there's somekind of error. chown and chgrp
		follows this style, but for the "Amiga-style" I implemented
		this option.
		With the verbose option you can force chown and chgrp to
		report their progress.
		To get some more "Amiga-like" commands you can define these
		aliases (if you're not used to UNIX this might be a good
		idea):
			alias chown "chown -v"
			alias chgrp "chgrp -v"

	   -R	Recursive
		Recursively change the ownerID and/or groupID for all files
		and directories encountered.

  chown  and  chgrp understands all the standard AmigaDos wildcards and you
can specify as many files and/or wildcards as your shell allows you.

  These  commands require Kickstart 3.0 or greater to function, if you're a
2.0 user you should use chown37 and chgrp37 instead.
@endnode

